
The core Wasm backend owns HIR-to-Wasm-LIR lowering, Wasm runtime contracts, request validation, debug output and optional binary emission.

The HTML-Wasm path is builder orchestration around that backend.
It chooses exports, requests helpers, invokes Wasm lowering, generates bootstrap JS and assembles route artifacts.

## Main paths

- `src/backends/wasm/`
- `src/projects/html_project/wasm/`
- `src/backends/wasm/hir_to_lir/ownership.rs`

## Core backend boundary

The core Wasm backend should consume validated HIR and companion metadata.
It should not rediscover frontend imports, source config, trait evidence, generic calls or template syntax.

It owns target-specific lowering from HIR into Wasm-facing lower IR and final Wasm artifacts when requested.

## HTML-Wasm path

The HTML-Wasm path is project-builder orchestration around the core Wasm backend. It:

- selects exported functions for the route artifact
- requests helper exports
- invokes core Wasm lowering
- generates bootstrap JavaScript
- assembles route HTML, JS and Wasm files using the same shared page-fragment contract as HTML-JS

The builder owns fragment planning and route assembly: the core Wasm backend owns HIR-to-Wasm lowering. Don't mix HTML-Wasm bootstrap policy into core Wasm lowering.

## Runtime contracts

The Wasm backend owns runtime contracts needed by generated code.
That includes helper exports and any target-specific runtime shape needed for strings, memory, calls or future ownership-aware lowering.

Backend feature validation should reject unsupported reachable features before lowering.
For example, builtin hashmap V1 targets HTML-JS, so HTML-Wasm rejects reachable map use before backend lowering until equivalent support exists.

## Ownership hook point

`src/backends/wasm/hir_to_lir/ownership.rs` is the ownership-fact projection
seam for Wasm lowering.

Ownership-aware lowering may use borrow facts and memory-model metadata for optimisation.
It must preserve the GC semantic baseline.
If ownership eligibility can't be proven, a value stays GC-managed.

No source-visible lifetime syntax or move syntax should leak out of this backend work.

## Common mistakes

- Mixing HTML-Wasm bootstrap policy into core Wasm lowering.
- Letting Wasm lowering accept features backend validation should reject.
- Treating ownership lowering as required for correctness.
- Reinterpreting source templates or imports in the Wasm backend.
- Generating separate semantics for GC and ownership paths.

